Spring Framework (annotation-based confi.evidence:
The `@Configuration` and `@Bean` annotations were introduced in Spring Framework 3.0, released in December 2009. These annotations enable Java-based configuration, allowing developers to define beans and their dependencies directly within Java classes, thereby reducing the need for XML configuration. ([docs.spring.io](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/reference/core/beans/java/basic-concepts.html?utm_source=openai))

The `@Configuration` annotation marks a class as a source of bean definitions, while the `@Bean` annotation is used on methods within these classes to define individual beans. This approach provides a more type-safe and refactor-friendly alternative to traditional XML-based configuration. ([docs.spring.io](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/reference/core/beans/java/basic-concepts.html?utm_source=openai))

For example, a simple configuration class using these annotations would look like this:

```java
@Configuration
public class AppConfig {
    @Bean
    public MyService myService() {
        return new MyServiceImpl();
    }
}
```

This configuration is equivalent to the following XML-based configuration:

```xml
<beans>
    <bean id="myService" class="com.acme.services.MyServiceImpl"/>
</beans>
```

By adopting `@Configuration` and `@Bean`, Spring developers can leverage the full power of Java to configure their applications, leading to cleaner and more maintainable codebases. ([docs.spring.io](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/reference/core/beans/java/basic-concepts.html?utm_source=openai))

Spring MVC @PostMapping and @GetMapping.evidence:
Spring's `@GetMapping` and `@PostMapping` annotations were introduced in version 4.3 of the Spring Framework, released in June 2016. ([docs.spring.io](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/4.3.16.RELEASE/spring-framework-reference/pdf/spring-framework-reference.pdf?utm_source=openai)) These annotations serve as shortcuts for `@RequestMapping` with specific HTTP methods, enhancing code readability and maintainability.

Prior to this, developers used `@RequestMapping` with the `method` attribute to specify the HTTP method, such as:

```java
@RequestMapping(value = "/example", method = RequestMethod.GET)
public String handleGetRequest() {
    // handle GET request
}
```

With the introduction of `@GetMapping` and `@PostMapping`, the code becomes more concise and expressive:

```java
@GetMapping("/example")
public String handleGetRequest() {
    // handle GET request
}
```

This change aligns with Spring's ongoing efforts to simplify and modernize its programming model.
